# Exercise 1.2.13

## (a)

The base case, i.e. $(A_1)^c = A_1^c$, is self-evident. 

For the inductive hypothesis, assume that for some $k \in \mathbb{N}^{\geq 2}$

```math
(A_1 \cup A_2 \cup \dots \cup A_k)^c = (A_1^c \cap A_2^c \cap \dots \cap A_k^c)
```

Now for the inductive step, observe that

```math
(A_1 \cup A_2 \cup \dots \cup A_k \cup A_{k + 1})^c = ((A_1 \cup A_2 \cup \dots \cup A_k) \cup A_{k + 1})^c
```

by repeated application of the associative set identity

```math
A \cup B \cup C = (A \cup B) \cup C
```

And by the following DeMorgan identity from Exercise 1.2.5, 

```math
(A \cup B)^c = A^c \cap B^c
```

we have

```math
((A_1 \cup A_2 \cup \dots \cup A_k) \cup A_{k + 1})^c = (A_1 \cup A_2 \cup \dots \cup A_k)^c \cap A_{k + 1}^c
```

Now, by the inductive hypothesis,

```math
(A_1 \cup A_2 \cup \dots \cup A_k)^c \cap A_{k + 1}^c = (A_1^c \cap A_2^c \cap \dots \cap A_k^c) \cap A_{k + 1}^c 
```

and repeated application of the associative set identity

```math
A \cap B \cap C = (A \cap B) \cap C
```

we can say

```math
(A_1^c \cap A_2^c \cap \dots \cap A_k^c) \cap A_{k + 1}^c = (A_1^c \cap A_2^c \cap \dots \cap A_k^c \cap A_{k + 1}^c)
```

proving the proposition.
